uhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the nearly three decades since German reunification, there remains little understanding of the ways in which experiences overlapped across East-West divides. German Division as Shared Experience considers everyday life across the two Germanies, using perspectives from history, literary and cultural studies, anthropology and art history to explore how interconnections as well as fractures between East and West Germany after 1945 were experienced, lived and felt. Through its novel approach to historical method, the volume points to new understandings of the place of narrative, form and lived sensibility in shaping Germans’ simultaneously shared and separate experiences of belonging during forty years of division from 1945 to 1990.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aIntercultural communicationzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aIntercultural communicationzGermany (West)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aCultural Practice.  aEast German.  aPostwar.  aWest German.1 aArmbruster, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellotti, Alissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Erica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEisman, April A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarcher, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMurtry, Áine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNössig, Franziska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmowski, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary